</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="12" pageNumber="13" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1438,152,683]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[197,320,541,567]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Remarks.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Scarbrough &amp; Perez-Gelabert" authorityYear="2009" box="[328,513,542,567]" class="Insecta" family="Asilidae" genus="Efferia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="angusta">
<emphasis box="[328,513,542,567]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Efferia angusta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is most similar to 
<taxonomicName box="[739,879,542,567]" class="Insecta" family="Asilidae" genus="Efferia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="haitensis">
<emphasis box="[739,879,542,567]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">E. haitensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Scarbrough &amp; Perez-Gelabert" authorityYear="2009" box="[938,1058,542,567]" class="Insecta" family="Asilidae" genus="Efferia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="serrula">
<emphasis box="[938,1058,542,567]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">E. serrula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but is distinguished from these and other congeners by the characters in the key and combined characters of the terminalia (
<figureCitation box="[1252,1368,580,606]" captionStart="FIGURES 5–8" captionStartId="11.[151,269,1651,1675]" captionTargetBox="[161,1424,376,1602]" captionTargetId="figure@11.[151,1436,349,1628]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURES 5–8. Efferia angusta sp. nov. Male terminalia, lateral view: 5. Intact, left side; 6. Gonostylus; 7. Phallus; and 8. Aedeagus with tubes and phallic flange." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1455814/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Figs. 5–8</figureCitation>
). The male is further distinguished by the mostly black vestiture of the head, exceptionally long setae of the scutellum, mostly black vestiture of the pleura, and bristly setae along the lateral margins of tergites 4–5
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
